        description: "By the end of this module, you will have a deeper understanding of the key concepts covered in this topic and be able to apply them in your champion role.",
        content: "# The Champion Role\n\n## Learning objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you will have a deeper understanding of the key concepts covered in this topic and be able to apply them in your champion role.\n\n## Core content\n\nWhat the neurodiversity champion role involves, the skills it develops, and how to get started. Champions are visible, informed, approachable people who bridge the gap between policy and practice. The role involves visibility, signposting, awareness raising, listening, and feeding back themes. It does not involve diagnosing, counselling, or replacing HR. Time commitment is roughly two to four hours per month. Key skills include active listening, understanding workplace barriers, confident supportive conversations, knowledge of rights and processes, and awareness of when to escalate.\n\n## Reflection questions\n\n1. How does this topic connect to your experience in the workplace?\n2. What is one thing you could apply from this module in the next week?\n3. What questions do you still have?\n\n## Further resources\n\nRefer to the Champions Hub for practical tools and templates related to this topic.\n",
